Date: xiv (late)

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 434 opens with a dialogue between a brother and sister regarding the sister's desire to learn about the Christian faith, with the result that the brother translates for her parts of the New Testament. The book contains a Middle English translation of the Catholic Epistles, Epistles of Paul, Acts of the Apostles, and part of St. Matthew's Gospel. The text has been edited by Anna Paues, and is also in Cambridge, Selwyn Coll. 108.L.19. The manuscript dates from c. 1400.

defendentem , et ex quorum lectione agnoscitur palatinus miles fuisse


Translation:

Prudentius, a learned man of secular literature, composed the Dittochæon. He discussed the Old and New Testaments with the personae having been cut out and, in the custom of the Greeks, the Hexameron about the creation of world up to the creation of the first man and his transgression, and he composed books which he entitled with the Greek names Apotheosis, Psychomachia, and Hamartigenia, that is, Concerning Divinity, Concerning the Fighting of the Soul, Concerning the Origin of Sins. He also made In Praise of Martyrs under the names of others: one book invitation to the martyr and the other of hymns, nevertheless with the special condition Against Symmachus who was defending idolatry and from reading those it is known that he was a palatine knight.


Comments: Batman has copied Gennadius’s inscription in the lower margin. Abbreviations follow those in the copied inscription. Tyronian ‘et’ in first three lines only.  Final three lines more characteristic of Batman’s hand than first three.

Contents: Old English Homilies

 

Date: cent. xii

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 303 is an interesting witness to the fate of the Old English language after the Norman Conquest led to the replacement of much of the English elite with French-speaking Normans. Manuscripts of Old English homilies were still produced at least as frequently as they had been in the period before the Conquest; contrary to popular misconception Old English seems to have continued in use. MS 303 is a collection of Old English homilies, many of them by Ælfric of Eynsham (c. 950-c. 1010), copied in the first half of the twelfth century in the south east of England, probably at Rochester. An old foliation shows that several quires have been lost from the start of this manuscript. Parker gave it the number 9 in his collection of homiletic manuscripts.

Hunc Authorem in quibusdam libris tradunt Authorem esse Johannem Anglicum |

ut habetur in exemplari scripto Magistri Richardi Prise / in Wallia / qui habet plures | 

libros usque ad [blank] inter quos capite 49 habentur quedam gravamina 9 scilicet | 

monachorum Sancti Edmundi contra Willelmum Bateman episcopum Norwicensem circa |

Translation:

In certain books, they say that this author was John of England, as it is said in the written exemplar of Master Richard Prise in Wales. He has many books, all the way to [blank]; among which, in the 49th chapter, some 9 grievances are contained, namely of the monks of St. Edmunds against William Bateman, the bishop of Norwich, around the year 1344, when the charters of many kings and bishops concerning the liberties of the aforesaid monastery are also recorded.

Archaizing Anglo-Saxon minuscule
Aspect: upright, well spaced
Graphs:
s - sigmoid s, rounded bowls, left leaning

yogh - rounded, flat-top with a hooked, right leaning approach stroke, tail of descender curls right

Contents: Works by Hugh of Saint-Victor OSA, Augustine, Alexander of Canterbury OSB, and others

 

Date: cent. xiii (early)

 

Full Description: The ex libris inscription of this thirteenth-century manuscript gives it a provenance at the Dominican convent, London. However, on f. ivr is a fragment of a deed, dated to 1515, in the name of the public notary of Norwich diocese, suggesting that the manuscript may have been in Norwich in the early sixteenth century. The manuscript contains Hugh of Saint-Victor OSA (c. 1096-1141) on the Celestial Hierarchy by pseudo-Dionysius, as well as numerous texts by Augustine, pseudo-Augustine, Isidore of Seville (c. 560-636), Jerome, Drogo of Laon (fl. c. 1100) and others. The final section of the manuscript is the only extant copy of the first recension of Alexander of Canterbury (fl. 1100-1110), Liber ex dictis beati Anselmi.

Shelfmark: Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, MS

 

Contents: Martianus Capella, De nuptiis Philologiae et Mercurii; Glossary on Martianus Capella

Date: cent. xi–xii

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 330 consists of two parts. Although they are appropriately associated since one contains a gloss on the text found in the other, they were originally separate manuscripts. The first part, written either in Normandy or in England probably in the early twelfth century, contains the De nuptiis Philologiae et Mercurii by the late antique author, Martianus Capella. It has an ex libris inscription of Malmesbury abbey, and contains writing in the hand of William of Malmesbury OSB (c. 1080-1143). It may have been William himself who combined it with the second part, which contains a commentary on Martianus Capella probably either by Dunchad (9th century) or Martin of Laon. The same text is found in CCCC MS 153. This second part was written on the Continent in the late ninth century (although Bischoff does not mention it in his catalogue of ninth-century manuscripts, which may mean he thought it later), but it was probably brought to England relatively early.

Contents: Lives of Saints

 

Date: cent. xii (late) and xiii (early)

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 161 is a collection of Saints' Lives which has been dated to c.1200. The provenance of the manuscript has been the subject of some debate; the Cluniac monastery at Faversham, Kent has been identified as the possible place of origin, and it seems that the manuscript was later at Canterbury. The majority of the Lives in the collection are of English or British saints, including Aldhelm, David, Dunstan, Ithamar, Neot, and Swithun, but four Cluniac saints are also included, which supports the connection with Faversham. Faversham is in the diocese of Rochester whose cathedral contained the relics of the rarely mentioned Ithamar. According to Lapidge, many of the vitae are somewhat abbreviated. The frontispiece depicts a bishop, and it has been suggested that this may be St Dunstan.

Contents: Iohannes de Sacro Bosco, Tractatus de sphaera. Alexander de Villa Dei, Algorismus. Richard of Bury, Philobiblon. Secreta Secretorum

 

Date: cent. xiv (late?)

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 456 is a late fourteenth-century manuscript that contains miscellaneous texts, some of them scientific. These include Iohannes de Sacro Bosco (fl. early thirteenth century), Tractatus de sphaera, the treatise by Richard of Bury (1281-1345) on the collection and study of books, the Philobiblon, Alexander de Villa Dei (c. 1170-c. 1240) Algorismus, and the Latin translation of the Arabic version of the Secretum secretorum by Philip of Tripoli (fl. c. 1243), which is also in CCCC MS 407. This last work, popular in the later Middle Ages, is a compilation of advice on political and ethical matters directed towards rulers. In addition, there are three anonymous astronomical and mathematical treatises. Of all of these texts, it was surely Richard of Bury's Philobiblon that attracted Parker to this manuscript, since the Archbishop and the erstwhile bishop of Durham shared a love of books not simply for their contents, but as objects in themselves.

Manuscript

 

Shelfmark: Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, MS 329

 

Contents: John Bramis, Historia regis Waldei. Chronicle (incarnation to 1415). Geoffrey de Rocherio

 

Date: cent. xv (early)

 

Full Description: The provenance of CCCC MS 329 gives every appearance of being firmly established as originating from the Benedictine priory of Thetford (Norfolk). Written c. 1425-50, the manuscript contains a number of texts associating it with the priory of the Blessed Virgin Mary. These include a statement about the authorship of John Bramis (fl. fourteenth century) of the Historia regis Waldei, to the unique copy of the History of Thetford priory by Geoffrey of Rocherio OSB (d. 1301), both texts found in this volume. There is also an anonymous account of a miracle attending the repairs carried out on the buildings of the priory. Yet, as James observed, another anonymous Chronicle from the incarnation to the year 1399, that also appears in this manuscript, takes a close interest in the affairs of the nearby priory of Augustinian canons at Ixworth (Suffolk). Parker no doubt valued it for its account of church history from his home county of Norfolk, but how it came into his possession is not known.

Manuscript

 

Shelfmark: Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, MS 386

 

Contents: Collectanea quaedam de metro et verso. Synonyma. Alanus ab Insula (Alain de Lille), Liber parabolarum. Verses

 

Date: cent. xiv and xv (late)

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 386 is prefaced by a printed version of an English translation of the works of Terence (195-159 B.C), which appears to be the only surviving copy of this edition of the text. This is followed by a manuscript collection of fourteenth and fifteenth-century treatises on the various disciplines of written composition and aids to producing texts. These include De metro, a text on metre and scansion, the Synonyma, frequently attributed to John of Garland (d. c. 1272), an incomplete version of Alanus ab Insula (Alain de Lille, c. 1128-1203) Liber parabolarum, and a collection of verses. The dating for this last section has been suggested as c. 1475-1500.

 

Sixteenth-Century Scribal Additions

 

Folio (or Page) r/v: fol. i r

 

Scribe: Stephan Batman

 

Script:

 

Hand:

 

Subject: Note on texts in second volume

 

Transcription:

Hic libellus vilis videri potest, sed nullus |

liber tam humilis est quin ejus aliquis |

usus esse potest, ut in hoc videre licet |

artem componendorum et carminum qua usi |

sunt poetae posterioris temporis in |

versibus suis resonantibus, fortasse |

non facile reperias alibi rationem qua |

usi sunt. |

Hic liber exemplum esse potest ne facile |

contemnatur scriptum etiamsi facie inculta

Translation:

 

Comments: Hand has strong italic influence. This is a note on the Armachanus, i.e the charges laid against the mendicant friars by the archishop of Armagh. It is from a copy of the Chronicon Anglia 1328-1388 but not the one edited by E.M. Thompson, ie. Harley MS 3634 - which has sixteenth-century manuscript additions. Thompson's account is hard to follow but involve copies of Stow, Foxe and Parker - and explanation of relationship to Walsingham i.e. CCC MS 240 and Chronicle of St Alban's ie. CCC MS 7).

Translation:

Odo the Severe, descended from the Danes in the eastern region of the Angles (East Anglia) and most learned in the Greek and Latin languages, composed one book about the Eucharist. Contents: Lives of Saints and Romances

 

Date: cent. xii

 

Full Description: The two parts of CCCC MS 318 may once have been separate manuscripts, but they were certainly together at Rochester in the twelfth century, when a contents list and an anathema were added to the volume. The first part is a twelfth-century collection of hagiography containing vitae of Edward the Confessor, Anselm of Canterbury, Herluin of Bec, and the Venerable Bede. The second part is also a twelfth-century collection of hagiography, but with some romance material as well: it contains texts on James the apostle, Charlemagne and Roland, Bishop Turpin, Thecla, and Apollonius of Tyre. An inscription says that the manuscript was given to Parker by a deacon of Rochester.

Subject: English translation of Prologue to Jean Galopes, Le livre doré de la vie de nostre seigneur Jesu Crist

 

Transcription: God, myne eyes, that is to saie, my vnderstanding and affectioun, are come to the earlie in the morning from my youth, to meditate and to thinck of thy worthie saying / Lex tua meditatio mea est. Thy lawe (my God) is my thought and meditacion. This meditacion shewith you to be a Lover of God, for that meditacion is a Loving cogitacion and a true waie to health. The reasoun is this, for that this meditacion ongendreth know // ledge / knowledge bringeth remorse / Remorse, devotion and devotion willeth praier. It is so than, that knowledge repelleth ignoraunce / Remorse driveth awaie naughtynes and sleuthfulnes and devotioun doth perfecte praier. And therfore he that attoyneth to this meditacion, he cometh to the vnder//standing and knowledge of hym sealf/ By the which contritioun followith. Who throughe consideracion of evill commytted, towched in his courage with sorrowe, devotioun moveth hym, whome the feare of the greatenes of those evill/, and the distrust of his owne strenght couverteth to God by praier; by the which God is moved to pardone hym. And in this meditacion men ought diligentlie to exercise them sealves a long while and to haue no trust in their owne wytt, who wolde attayne the fruyte therof. The which is good to be the mortyfying of the the fleshe and lifting vpp of the thought to the accomplishement of the Lawe bothe olde and newe: and to the exhibiting of praise and thancks. Beatus qui legit et audit verba prophetie huius, et seruat omnia que in ea scripta sunt. Apoc: 1. Cap. And therfore blessed is he whiche readeth and heareth the wordes of this book yf he observe and exequite all thinges written therin. And therfore most high, most excellent and mightie prince, considering the verie truth hereof and the greate profitt that shall follow, I haue translated this book at your commaundement owt of Latyne into french vnder your correction to the profitt of all and to the honour of God, who graunte you to Reigne well, Lyve well and dye well. Amen./

Date: cent. xii (early)

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 457 is an early twelfth-century copy of the second recension of Alexander of Canterbury OSB (fl. early twelfth century), Liber ex dictis beati Anselmi, including the Miracula. The scholarly circle around Anselm (archbishop of Canterbury 1093-1109) produced several writings which contain material derived from the archbishop's own teachings, of which this is one. This manuscript was used by the editors to provide the base text for the second recension. It has early provenance at Christ Church, Canterbury in the form of an erased ex libris inscription and a classmark in the early form ".AN.". It later came into the hands of Matthew Parker, who rewrote some parts and provided an inscription erroneously attributing the work to Eadmer of Canterbury OSB (d. after 1124).

Date: cent. xv (early)

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 213 is a copy of Jean Galopes, Le livre doré de la vie de nostre seigneur Jesu Crist, made for presentation to Henry V probably c. 1420, which is depicted in a miniature at the beginning of the book. The dating of the book is after 1419 when Rouen surrendered to the English and Normandy came under the custody of the uncle of Henry V, Thomas Beaufort, duke of Exeter, who together with the king is mentioned in the presentation inscription. The text is a translation into French by Jean Galopes of the pseudo-Bonaventuran Meditationes uitae Christi, an expanded version of the Gospel account of the life of Christ, whose Latin text has been attributed to John de Caulibus OFM. Jean Galopes was dean of the collegiate church of St Louis de Saulsoye in the diocese of Evreux in Normandy.

Manuscript

 

Shelfmark: Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, MS 161

 

Contents: Lives of Saints

 

Date: cent. xii (late) and xiii (early)

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 161 is a collection of Saints' Lives which has been dated to c.1200. The provenance of the manuscript has been the subject of some debate; the Cluniac monastery at Faversham, Kent has been identified as the possible place of origin, and it seems that the manuscript was later at Canterbury. The majority of the Lives in the collection are of English or British saints, including Aldhelm, David, Dunstan, Ithamar, Neot, and Swithun, but four Cluniac saints are also included, which supports the connection with Faversham. Faversham is in the diocese of Rochester whose cathedral contained the relics of the rarely mentioned Ithamar. According to Lapidge, many of the vitae are somewhat abbreviated. The frontispiece depicts a bishop, and it has been suggested that this may be St Dunstan.

 

Sixteenth-Century Scribal Additions

 

Folio (or Page) r/v: fol. i r

 

Scribe: Stephan Batman

 

Script: secretary

 

Hand:

 

Subject:

 

Transcription:

Quamvis hec legenda Sanctorum vt |

vocant, a multis contemnantur , tamen quia |

in ijs aliquid historie continetur, non |

sint negligenda, vnde possis vel |

verum videre vel antiquorum super= |

stitionem notare . / .


Translation:

Although these legends of the saints, as they are called, are disdained by many, nevertheless they should not be neglected because some history is contained in them, from which you may perceive the truth or observe the superstition of the ancients.

 

Comments: Folio also contains "Twyne" in red chalk. John Twyne collected MSS for Parker.

Date: xiii (early) 

Date: xv

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 425 consists of two once-separate volumes. The first contains the unique surviving copies of two hagiographical works by Gerald of Wales (1146-1226), his lives of St Remigius and St Hugh. It has been suggested that the manuscript could be an autograph, and on these grounds has been located to Lincoln between 1209 and 1223. The second volume is a c. 1450 copy of letters of Peter of Blois (d. 1212). The two were probably combined by Matthew Parker. He added a table of contents and the initials "TW" to the start of the first volume, perhaps suggesting that he acquired it from one of the Twynes or from Thomas Wootton.

In gratiam eorum qui huius modi abbreuiationibus antiquorum non sunt exercitati

 

Duo sunt Imperator Auguste, quibus hic mundus regitur |

Sacerdotium et reginum. Sacerdos orat. Rex imperat |

Sacerdos peccata vel debita dimittit. Rex errata punit. |

Sacerdos animam ligat et soluit.  Rex corpora cruciat |

et occidit. Vterque divine legis executor suum Iusticie |

debitum cuique tribuit, malos cohercendo, et bonos re=|

munerando. Quippe diuisum imperium cum Iove Cesar habens. |

Terrena moderatur, et lutea figmenta iudicat. |

hec probans ista conterens, Sacerdos animas informat |

spiritus divini seminis ubertate recreat, dum celum celi |

domino, Terram autem dedit filiis hominum, Sane |

filios hominum decent arma et sagitte, filios Dei ora= |

tiones vota et sacrificia, ut Carbones succendantur ab

 eis: dum vita pastoris doctrina est pasturalis ovibus, |

et rigor punientis pax est popularis, porro sacerdotio |

regnum se noverit adesse non preesse; Adici non prefici |

in executionem dari, per adiutorim non in maiori tatem |

efferri per dominationis authoritatem. Constituens enim |

dominus corpus in homine et animam in vtroque per |

prevaricationem suam lesam sentiens maiestatem, corpora |

dedit legem talionis, et anime satisfactionem contritionis |

cum adiuncta verecundia confessionis, secundum id apostolic |

quem enim fructum tunc habuistis in quibus nunc eru= |

bescitis. Sunt ergo prius corpus ex lutea formatur |

materia et ex hinc anima vasi infunditur nec tamen |

anima corporis inclusa carcere corpori debet subesse |

Sed carnis opera regendo ad mensuram rationis |

dispondre: Ita Rex sacerdotium ante tempus logis |

Mosaice in belo it nino assiriorum rege primo predens |

Ad hominum studens oppressionem non antefertur digni= |

tate sed etate fortius, quis rex iste summus summus et |

sacerdos christus secundum ordinem Melchisedech suo. |

sacerdotium consecrauit imperio, sortem suam in clero con= |

stituens, cuius merito clerici in sortem domini vocati nuncupantur |

 

Comments: transcription of the opening portion of the text which begins on the facing recto page (for helping readers who are unfamiliar with the abbreviations).

‘In gratiam eorum qui huius modi abbreuiationibus antiquorum non sunt exercitati’ in cursive Italic, remainder in Elizabethan Secretary.

Subject: English translation of Prologue to Jean Galopes, Le livre doré de la vie de nostre seigneur Jesu Crist

 

Transcription: witt, savorie science, whiche is not onelie speculatiue, but for the love of God, his true frynde, comaunded to disclose and by this knowledge you shall remaine in truthe, for the whiche you shall fight, and god shall give you strenght and vertue, and so longe as you shalbe in the truthe, you shall governe well your lande, and shalbe called king of the Earth. To the good governement wherof is Justise requisite, mixte with mercie of the which Justice speaketh St. Augustine also in the .ix/th\. chapter of the Book of the Twelve Abusions. Justicia Regis est neminem iniuste per potenciam opprimere sine perfonarum excepcione iuste indicare etcetera. The Justice of the king saith he, is not to oppresse any vniustlie by might and force, but iustlie to Judge withowt regarde of persones, to be a defendour of the fatherles and widoos to correcte Robberies to punyshe advlteries: and not to advaunce the wicked: to nowrishe the poore, by almes deedes: to constitute and appointe iuste men over the affaires of the kingdome: to haue sobre wyse men of mature age to his counsilours: to be slowe to wrathe: stronglie and iustlie to defende his Countrie: and to fortifie hym sealf and putt his whole trust in God: In prosperitie not to be prowd and in all adversities to be pacient: To defende the catholique faithe: not to suffer any eville to be done to his children: and at certein howres to praieto God. By the which Justice, mingled (as it is said, with mercie, you shall doo the will of God, even as the said St. Augustine saith in his Book of Wholesome Counseill / Tunc erit vobis pax in circuitu et securitas summa etcetera. Then shall you haue peace rounde aboute you and greate securitie, and you nede not feare any daunger. Then in syme and place shall you sett your hearte in his sovereigne meditacions, according to the xample of his humble prophite King David, who in the .118/th\. Psalme saith thus. Peruenerunt oculi mei ad te diluculo vt meditarer eloquia tua. Said David to God/

Hand:

s - pronounced forward-sloping stem

Transcription:

Hunc Authorem in quibusdam libris tradunt Authorem esse Johannem Anglicum |

ut habetur in exemplari scripto Magistri Richardi Prise / in Wallia / qui habet plures | 

libros usque ad [blank] inter quos capite 49 habentur quedam gravamina 9 scilicet | 

monachorum Sancti Edmundi contra Willelmum Bateman episcopum Norwicensem circa | 

Annum Domini 1344. Ubi etiam recitantur carte plurimorum regum et pontificum |

pro libertatibus predicti monasterii /


Translation:

In certain books, they say that this author was John of England, as it is said in the written exemplar of Master Richard Prise in Wales. He has many books, all the way to [blank]; among which, in the 49th chapter, some 9 grievances are contained, namely of the monks of St. Edmunds against William Bateman, the bishop of Norwich, around the year 1344, when the charters of many kings and bishops concerning the liberties of the aforesaid monastery are also recorded.

Contents: Ieuan ap Sulien's Augustine on the Trinity

 

Date: cent. xi

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 199 is a copy of Augustine of Hippo, De trinitate, made c. 1090 at Llanbadarn Fawr by Ieuan ap Sulien (d. 1137). Ieuan was from a prominent literary family; his brother, Rhigyfarch (d. 1099), wrote a Life of St David and succeeded his father, Sulien (d. 1091), as bishop of St David's. Some of Ieuan's own verses in Latin and Welsh survive in the margins of this manuscript, but unfortunately part of the Welsh verse was lost in 1953 when the manuscript was rebound. The main text of this manuscript is written in a very attractive hand, with some beautiful decorated initials. The flyleaf contains a ninth-century fragment of Smaragdus (fl. 809-17) in a Carolingian minuscule, possibly from Rheims.

Res sane notatu digna quod lingua anglicana in tantillo tempore |

videlicet infra Quadringentos annos possit tantam variationem verborum |

et phraseon pati / vt hic videre licet /

Translation:

It is certainly a worthy thing to note that the English language in such a short time, namely within 400 years, could undergo so much variation in words and phrases, as one may see here.

 

Comments: Batman includes some marginal glosses of archaic words on the same folio. (Do we want a separate annotation for these?) mankynd for mankunne; descended for aly3te, etc.

Contents: Richard FitzRalph, De pauperie Saluatoris

Date: s. xiv

Full Description: 
The De pauperie Saluatoris of Richard FitzRalph (d. 1360), archbishop of Armagh, contained in CCCC MS 382, is a text on the poverty of the mendicants in relation to the poverty taught by Christ, and the problems caused by their acquiring property and privilege. It is also found in CCCC MSS 103 and 180. The dating of this copy has been suggested as c. 1375-1400. It belonged to St Augustine's, Canterbury, and is in the fifteenth-century library catalogue of the abbey.

Contents: Macrobius, Saturnalia, Commentary on Cicero's Somnium Scipionis. Apuleius, De Platone, De deo Socratis

 

Date: cent. xii

 

Full Description: As an important witness to the twelfth-century interest in texts of classical Roman and late antique authors, CCCC MS 71 contains Macrobius, Saturnalia, Macrobius's commentary on Cicero's Somnium Scipionis, and Apuleius, Opera philosophica. The Apuleius texts belong to the third group of manuscripts of these works as classified by Beaujeu. The added thirteenth-century list of contents on the flyleaf is in a special form characteristic of the Abbey of St Albans. It is likely that the book was made at the abbey, although there is no firm evidence it was there until the thirteenth century when the contents were listed. Thomson, in his study of St Albans manuscripts, dates the book to c. 1150. On the flyleaf a fifteenth-century note values the book at xx s.

Date: cent. xv

 

Full Description: CCCC MS 142, dating to the fifteenth century, is a copy of translation by Nicholas Love OCarth (d. 1423/4) of the pseudo-Bonaventuran Meditationes uitae Christi, an expansion of the Gospel narrative of the life of Christ. This text in both its Latin versions and translations into the vernacular was very popular throughout Europe in the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries. Nicholas Love, a Carthusian, was prior of Mount Grace in Yorkshire. His translation of the Meditationes, The Mirrour of the blessyd Lyf of Christ, was submitted for approval to Archbishop Arundel in 1410, and the Memorandum of the licence of approval is in this manuscript.

Hunc Authorem in quibusdam libris tradunt Authorem esse Johannem Anglicum |

ut habetur in exemplari scripto Magistri Richardi Prise / in Wallia / qui habet plures | 

libros usque ad [blank] inter quos capite 49 habentur quedam gravamina 9 scilicet | 

monachorum Sancti Edmundi contra Willelmum Bateman episcopum Norwicensem circa | 

Annum Domini 1344. Ubi etiam recitantur carte plurimorum regum et pontificum |

pro libertatibus predicti monasterii /


Translation:

In certain books, they say that this author was John of England, as it is said in the written exemplar of Master Richard Prise in Wales. He has many books, all the way to [blank]; among which, in the 49th chapter, some 9 grievances are contained, namely of the monks of St. Edmunds against William Bateman, the bishop of Norwich, around the year 1344, when the charters of many kings and bishops concerning the liberties of the aforesaid monastery are also recorded.

 

Comments: On this folio one of Parker’s scribes has copied the entry concerning John of Tynemouth provided by Bale, adding a reference to Bale’s work in the margin. Below this Stephen Batman has appended the subject annotation

Subject: English translation of Prologue to Jean Galopes, Le livre doré de la vie de nostre seigneur Jesu Crist


Transcription: Here begynneth the golden Booke of the meditacone of the lyffe of our Salviour Jesue Christ Wrytten by Bonauenture. And fyrst the Prologue of the Translator. To the most highe, most myhtie and most victorious Prime, Henry the fyft of that name, by the grace of God kinge of England, Heyre and Regiant of Fraunce, and Duke of Irelande / your humble Chapleyne Johannis Galopes called Gaulois Deane of the Collegeall churche of St. Lewis of Saulseye or Diocese of Deurox in your Duchie of Normandie in the Landes of the Counte of Harecourte apperteyning to the most excellent and puyssant Prynce my Deare Lorde, my Lord the Duk of Excetor your greate vncle, wissheth you alle honour, obedience and subiection./ Moste renoumed and suffereigne Lorde according to that, which the Scripture saithe in the .XXV/th\. of the prouerbes: Gloria Regum est inuestigare sermonem. The glorie of kinges who wolde wysly governe them selves and their subiectes, is to serche and inquire the sense of the diuine worde, the whiche vnderstoode, they ought to honour, as also honour is due to vertue, not onely moralle, but that whiche is intelligible: And therfore blessed be the sovereigne Emperour and king of kinges, God, our cheiff Lord vnder whome alle mortalle kinges Live and Reigne / when he wille inclyne your hearte, to haue the glorie above saints, to cause to be putt into the frenche tongue the Golden book of the meditacions of the liff of our salviour Jesus Christ; Wrytten by the yeuth doctor of good memorie Bonauenture the author therof for hy contemplacion therin, ye maie haut knowledge of the divine dedes and sayinges, whiche is proprely wysdome. That is to witt.
